	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />(Darn it. Denine, ninja'd me here... and then Dwedit. I write too much.)<br />I'm also with Tepples on &quot;this post&quot;. I too see it like handing someone information or pointing to something and saying &quot;read this.&quot; So it works just as well for me when read aloud. But I guess it's strange... read that would be used (by me at least) interchangeably in a  &quot;real life&quot; situation like the above (Throw article on someone's desk. &quot;Read that and get back to me&quot;), but it sounds wrong to me online. <br /><br />If you replaced page with article in your example, blargg, it would make sense. Only certain words create the ambiguous situation you're concerned about. <br /><br />I sometimes do something like this:<br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent"><!-- m --><a class="postlink" href="http://www.aseprite.org/">http://www.aseprite.org/</a><!-- m --><br /><br />That program is a really cool pixel animation program.<br /></div><br />But I would not do this:<br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent"><a href="http://www.aseprite.org/" class="postlink">That program</a> is a really cool pixel animation program.<br /></div><br />I'm not sure why I wouldn't do the second one, or even why I prefer the first. I prefer &quot;this program&quot; with a link to both of the &quot;that&quot; solutions, though.<br /><br />Edit: And now I'm considering other forms of self referential text. <br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">This book contains a list of excellent resources for programming. <br />Made Up Title C Book:<br />This book is excellent in that it teaches blah blah in a basic way.<br /></div><br />Heh. So I guess it is weird in context like that, and I just didn't notice it on forums. Is using &quot;that&quot; really the &quot;proper&quot; way?<br />Edit2: And again, it's only weird when the types of works are the same.<br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">This book contains a list of excellent resources for programming. <br />Microsoft Visual Studio 2010:<br />This program is excellent because blah blah blah.<br /></div><br />I wouldn't bat an eyelash at the above. Weird!  <img src="./images/smilies/icon_lol.gif" alt=":lol:" title="Laughing" /> For the above examples you could just use the name of the works in question instead of this or that, but that's not so for posts. Maybe I'll start using &quot;In a post by X&quot;.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
