	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">Kasumi wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent"><!-- m --><a class="postlink" href="http://www.aseprite.org/">http://www.aseprite.org/</a><!-- m --><br /><br />That program is a really cool pixel animation program.<br /></div><br />But I would not do this:<br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent"><a href="http://www.aseprite.org/" class="postlink">That program</a> is a really cool pixel animation program.<br /></div><br />I'm not sure why I wouldn't do the second one, or even why I prefer the first. I prefer &quot;this program&quot; with a link to both of the &quot;that&quot; solutions, though.<br /></div><br />Yeah, those examples make a good point. To use &quot;that&quot;, you must have already established the referent. Doing it simultaneously with a link doesn't work. It seems best to use some descriptive text, like &quot;<a href="http://www.aseprite.org/" class="postlink">Aseprite</a> is a really cool pixel animation program.&quot; or &quot;In a [url=blabla]recent posting[/url] someone explained bla bla...&quot; You might then say &quot;that posting&quot; in the same paragraph, but the link would be on the first mention before you have anything to refer to with &quot;that&quot;. I still think that linked text starting with &quot;this&quot; is on the level of a &quot;here&quot; link, and that it subtly disrupts flow slightly by jumping abstraction levels. When I'm reading, I think of my comprehension working on several levels separately. Part is reading, another part is asking whether I know what's being referred to and seeing whether the thing mentioned is worth looking at. A &quot;this&quot; or &quot;click here&quot; is sort of like a dependency between them, which blocks one while the other figures out what it means.<br /><br />I'm just sharing my own thoughts and perceptions on the subject, and am finding others' ideas interesting. And yes, tepples' posting style is chock full of useful links to more information.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


